│ OrigLoop)) && \" VPlan cost model and legacy cost model disagreed\");\nThis   │
│ asserts that if the VPlan-based cost model selects a different VF than the    │
│ legacy cost model, the chosen BestPlan must contain additional                │
│ simplifications relative to the original loop. In the reproducer,             │
│ BestFactor.Width is a fixed VF=8 while LegacyVF.Width is a scalable VF=4, and │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(BestPlan, ...) returns false,           │
│ triggering the assertion.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe loop is minimal:    │
│ one dead load (first load result unused), one live load, an extend and a      │
│ store. The vectorizer builds multiple VPlans, including at least one with     │
│ fixed widths {2,4,8} and another with scalable VF=4. The VPlan-based cost     │
│ model chose fixed VF=8 with cost 15 and scalar cost 5; legacy cost model      │
│ chose scalable VF=4 with same cost numbers. The assertion expected equality   │
│ or simplifications in BestPlan; neither satisfied.\n\nDebugger locals         │
│ show:\nBestFactor.Width = fixed 8\nLegacyVF.Width = scalable 4\nCosts equal   │
│ (15), ScalarCost = 5.\nBestPlan VFs: {2,4,8 (all fixed)}; LegacyVF.Width      │
│ refers to a different plan containing scalable VF=4.\nThus disagreement       │
│ arises from selecting different plans, not from extra simplifications inside  │
│ BestPlan.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe assertion condition only examines   │
│ additional simplifications present in the BestPlan. It ignores the            │
│ possibility that the discrepancy in VF selection is due to simplifications    │
│ (or structural differences) present in the legacy-chosen plan versus the      │
│ VPlan-chosen plan. If the legacy plan lacks simplifications that the BestPlan │
│ exploits (or vice versa), the assertion still fires because it only checks    │
│ BestPlan. In this reproducer, the chosen BestPlan does not have extra         │
│ simplifications relative to the original loop, but a different plan (the one  │
│ yielding LegacyVF) may differ structurally (e.g., inclusion/exclusion of dead │
│ interleave group members or handling of the dead load). Since the             │
│ verification logic is asymmetric—only inspecting BestPlan—it treats any       │
│ difference caused by plan set divergence as a fatal disagreement.\nTherefore, │
│ the assertion is too strict: it should allow disagreement if either plan      │
│ involved (BestPlan or LegacyPlan) contains additional simplifications;        │
│ equivalently, the discrepancy must be justified by simplifications in at      │
│ least one of the plans. Additionally, the cost precomputation context         │
│ (CostCtx) is built only for BestPlan; using it to judge simplifications for   │
│ LegacyVF’s plan would be inaccurate. The code never inspects LegacyPlan for   │
│ simplifications.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Points:\nEdit lines 7389–7396 in         │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp to:\n- Precompute costs for   │
│ both BestPlan and LegacyPlan in separate VPCostContext instances.\n- Extend   │
│ assertion to allow VF mismatch if either the BestPlan OR the LegacyPlan       │
│ contains additional simplifications.\nCurrent lines (approx.):\n7389          │
│ VPCostContext CostCtx(CM.TTI, *CM.TLI, Legal->getWidestInductionType(),\n7390 │
│ LLVMCtx, CM);\n7391   precomputeCosts(BestPlan, BestFactor.Width,             │
